                            ],
                            "spans": [
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        204,
                                        1795,
                                        1252,
                                        2290
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "A key design point of MARLIN is to be trained and evaluated on real networks. Utilizing real components allowed us to understand the challenges that the CC domain brings to RL, avoiding the risk of failing a \"sim- to- real\" transposition, which could be caused, by inaccurate emulated/simulated patterns and weak assumptions, at the cost of a slower training time. Relying on real hardware and protocol implementation intrinsically diversifies training experience thanks to the stochasticity of the environment and it prevents the agent from overfitting on artificial patterns that would not be found in the real world."
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ],
                    "index": 4
                },
                {
                    "bbox": [
                        204,
                        2296,
                        1249,
                        2887
                    ],
                    "type": "text",
                    "lines": [
                        {
                            "bbox": [
                                204,
                                2296,
                                1249,
                                2887
                            ],
                            "spans": [
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        204,
                                        2296,
                                        1249,
                                        2887
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "To this end, we built the network shown in Fig. 2 which comprises two sources of traffic and two receivers, two WiFi Access Point (AP), two network switches, and one router connected in a dumbbell topology. Traffic sources are connected to the WiFi AP located at one end of the dumbbell, while traffic receivers are connected to the AP at the other end. The \"Background Traffic Source\", on the left, is responsible for generating background and send it to the \"Background Traffic Receiver\" node, on the right. The \"Sender Application\" transmits traffic to the \"Receiver Application\" via a custom transport protocol implementation that uses MARLIN as its CC algorithm."
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ],
                    "index": 5
                },
                {
                    "bbox": [
                        198,
                        2897,
                        1249,
                        2993
                    ],
                    "type": "text",
                    "lines": [
                        {
                            "bbox": [
                                198,
                                2897,
                                1249,
                                2993
                            ],
                            "spans": [
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        198,
                                        2897,
                                        1249,
                                        2993
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "The need for implementation flexibility led us to integrate MARLIN with Mockets, a protocol originally designed for "
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "bbox": [
                                1297,
                                927,
                                2351,
                                1669
                            ],
                            "spans": [
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "communication environments characterized by limited bandwidth, typically found in tactical and wireless sensor networks. Further details regarding Mockets are presented in Section III. To avoid running into situations where MARLIN could underperform due to the protocol implementation, we shaped the network scenario around the typical Mockets use case for this first iteration. We set a Smart Queue policy on the router to limit the maximum amount of traffic flowing between the two subnetworks to "
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "inline_equation",
                                    "content": "250\\mathrm{KB / s}"
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": "; we also used TC NetEm - Traffic Control Network Emulator (TC- NETEM) on the \"Sender Application\" node to introduce "
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "inline_equation",
                                    "content": "100\\mathrm{ms}"
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": " of latency and "
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "inline_equation",
                                    "content": "3\\%"
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": " random packet loss that only affect the traffic generated by the application. Note that the router's manual reports that it effectively limits the actual rate to "
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "inline_equation",
                                    "content": "95\\%"
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        1297,
                                        927,
                                        2351,
                                        1669
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": " of the specified value when Smart Queue is enabled [18]."
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ],
